Other cases of ‘bonitarian’ owner· ship, though less common than this, sprang up lrom the praetorias legal innovations, e. g. those ol praetorian universal succession in bankruptcy and upon death: in these the proper remedy was some other fictitious action <Gaius iv. 35).

ln the time ol Gaius this distinction between dominium ex iure Quiri· tium and in bonis habere is of every-day occurrence, but, except in respect of manumission (note on Bk. i. 5. 1 supr), the differences between them are not of any practical importance. When Justinian had abolished the old points of difference between solum Italicum and solum pro- vinciale (Tit. 6 pr. ini, Cod. 7. 3¹3 5. 13'. ις), and peregrini had practi- cally become unknown, all these refinements disappeared: there was hutone dominium leit; the only contrast was between it and possessio. The survival ol the actio Publiciana in the Corpus iuris is explained by Mt. Poste, Gaius p. 188.

Some ot' the modes in which ownership is acquired in res singulae are common to most systema of law: others are peculiar to this people or that. The former the Romans supposed to have been prescribed or sanctioned hy the law os nature, and therefore to be prior in time (vetustius ius) to those which are peculiar: ior a peculias mode oi ac· quisition exists only in virtue of municipal law or custom, which is itself the outcome ol political society, and political association was preceded in their view (derived from the Stoics, p. 3⁶ supr.) by ages in which nature’s was the only law, and civitates, magistratus, and leges had not yet come into existence. lt is hardly necessary to observe that this view is quite erroneous: the history oi Roman law alone might cou- vince us that among primitive peoples absolute private ownership isa thing at first unknown, and that when it has been developed, alienation is the exception, not the rule, and the modes in which it is effected formal and essentially ‘iuris civilis!
